  <h2 id="overview">What the canvas is</h2>

  <p>
    The canvas is an infinite, freeform board (pan, zoom, and drag) where the unit of work is an
    <strong>object</strong> rather than a single query tab. Each object sits at its own position and
    size and can overlap its neighbours. An object is one of six kinds today: a <strong>query</strong>
    that runs SQL, a <strong>table</strong> that previews another query's rows, a <strong>chart</strong>
    that visualizes another query's results, a block of <strong>text</strong>, a <strong>sticky
    note</strong>, or a simple <strong>shape</strong>. The kinds are designed to grow, so more object
    types can be added later.
  </p>

  <p>
    The point of the board is to assemble an analysis you can see all at once: the query that pulls
    the data, the chart that makes it legible, and the commentary that explains it, side by side. You
    can build that by hand, but the fastest path is to ask the agent.
  </p>

  <h2 id="opening">Opening a canvas</h2>

  <p>
    Open a new board with the <strong>New Canvas</strong> button (the sparkles icon) in the editor
    tab bar, or run the <strong>New Canvas</strong> command from the keymap. A canvas opens as a
    center tab, just like a query or a notebook, and you can rename it. The board starts on the
    connection that is currently selected, but the <strong>Connection</strong> picker at the top of
    the agent panel is a multi-select: choose several connections and the agent reads every one's
    schema and can run each query object against a different database. The first connection you pick
    is the primary, used as the default for query objects you add by hand. The set is saved with the
    board.
  </p>

  <h2 id="objects">Objects</h2>

  <DocTable>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Object</th>
        <th>What it does</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Query</td>
        <td>
          Holds one SQL statement with a <strong>Run</strong> button and a one-line run status. Its
          editor is the same CodeMirror as the main SQL editor, so you get the connection's dialect
          highlighting and schema-aware table and column autocomplete. It runs against the canvas's
          connection, the same engine the editor uses. The query object shows no rows itself: the
          first time you run it, Arris drops a preview <strong>table</strong> beside it (joined with an
          arrow) so the rows show without any extra step. Bind a chart to it instead if you want a
          visualization rather than a grid. A query can also read <strong>another query's result</strong>
          by its title: write <code>FROM &lt;other cell title&gt;</code> and that cell becomes an
          in-memory table. Running a query auto-runs the upstream cells it reads first, and a
          dependency arrow is drawn between them. (Joining a live database table and another cell's
          result in the same query is not supported yet; pull the live data into its own cell first.)
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Table</td>
        <td>
          Previews a query object's rows as a scrollable grid. A table is bound to its source query,
          so when that query runs the table updates. Pick its source in the properties pane.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Chart</td>
        <td>
          Visualizes a query object's results. A chart is bound to its source query, so when that
          query runs the chart updates. It uses the same chart engine as the results viewer.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Text</td>
        <td>Free text for headings and commentary. Double-click to edit in place.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Sticky note</td>
        <td>A coloured note for annotations, pinned on top of the board.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Shape</td>
        <td>
          A rectangle, ellipse, or line for grouping and annotation. Rectangles and
          ellipses hold optional centered text (double-click to add it), and a rectangle's
          corners can be rounded by dragging its radius handle.
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </DocTable>

  <h2 id="agent">Building with the agent</h2>

  <p>
    The <strong>Agent</strong> panel runs down the left of the board. Type a request, for example
    <em>"monthly sales by category"</em>, and the agent reads the connection's schema and replies
    with a set of objects to add. A typical answer is a query object (the SQL that aggregates your
    data), a chart object bound to it, and a short text summary. Arris places the new objects on the
    board, runs the query automatically, and the chart renders from the result.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pick the provider in the chat header, the same <strong>Codex</strong> or <strong>Claude</strong>
    choice as the SQL agent (it is one shared preference). The agent runs that provider's local CLI
    under the same guardrails as the SQL agent: it runs locally in a read-only mode, never touches
    your filesystem,
    and only receives your prompt, each chosen connection's <strong>schema as DDL</strong> and
    dialect, and a
    short summary of the objects already on the board (their kinds, ids, titles, and SQL), all capped
    in size. Your row data is not sent. Because the agent needs the schema to write correct SQL, the
    chat asks you to connect a database to the canvas first.
  </p>

  <p>
    When you pick connections, the panel shows a <strong>fetching schema</strong> indicator while it
    reads each database's tables and columns (the same deep read the schema browser does, not just the
    table names). Expand the collapsible <strong>Context</strong> section to preview the exact text
    handed to the agent: the schema DDL (one labeled block per connection) plus the current board
    summary, so you can see what it is working from. On a multi-connection board each block is headed
    with its connection's id and dialect, and the agent tags every query object it writes with the
    matching connection.
  </p>

  <p>
    Because each turn sees the current board, follow-up messages refine it in place rather than only
    piling on new objects. The agent can <strong>add</strong> any object kind (a query, table, chart,
    text block, sticky note, or shape), <strong>modify</strong> one that is already there (re-spec a chart
    as a line chart, restyle it (set axis bounds, toggle the legend, change colours), rewrite a
    query, retitle an object, move a query to a different connection), or <strong>remove</strong>
    objects you no longer want. A query the
    agent adds or changes runs automatically, and any chart bound to it updates.
  </p>

  <p>
    When the data you ask for can be derived from a query already on the board, the agent
    <strong>builds on that cell's results</strong> instead of re-querying the database: it writes a new
    query that selects <code>FROM</code> the existing cell (to filter, re-aggregate, reshape, or join
    cells), which runs in the in-memory engine. It falls back to a fresh database query only when no
    existing cell has the columns or grain it needs (a weekly-summed cell, for instance, cannot be
    split back into days).
  </p>

  <p>
    The agent sees your schema and the board, but never the rows a query returned. When it needs
    them, it <strong>asks</strong>: instead of changing the board it posts a <strong>Share
    results</strong> request naming the query objects it wants and why. A card appears in the chat
    with <strong>Share results</strong> and <strong>Decline</strong> buttons; click Share results and
    Arris sends those rows in the next message so the agent can write commentary or follow-up queries
    grounded in the real data. Sharing is never automatic: nothing leaves until you approve the
    request. (Asking the user is a general mechanism, so the agent can grow other question types over
    time; sharing results is the first.)
  </p>

  <h2 id="board">Working on the board</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Add</strong> objects from the toolbar at the bottom of the board: a query, table, chart, sticky note, text, or shape. New objects appear centered in your current view, not at a fixed origin, so they never land off-screen after you pan. Tools with a caret have options (the shape kind, the pointer mode): clicking the tool applies its last-used option and opens the menu at the same time, so switching to another option is one more click. The caret alone just toggles the menu. Single-key shortcuts drive the same actions (<kbd>V</kbd> move, <kbd>H</kbd> hand, <kbd>/</kbd> SQL cell, <kbd>R</kbd>/<kbd>O</kbd>/<kbd>L</kbd> shapes); the keys fire only while the board is focused, never while you are typing, and are rebindable under Settings.</li>
    <li><strong>Select</strong> an object with a single click; its resize anchors stay shown until you click an empty part of the board.</li>
    <li><strong>Adjust properties</strong> in the panel that opens on the right while one object is selected. Every object shows its position, size, and a lock toggle; below that each kind has its own controls (a shape's fill, stroke, and corner radius; a text block's font size, weight, alignment, and colour; a sticky note's tint; a query's title and connection; a table's source query and preview-row cap; a chart's source query plus the full chart
      editor: type, axes, series, aggregation, colours, legend, and labels, the same
      control surface as the results-view chart editor).</li>
    <li><strong>Move</strong> an object by dragging it; objects may overlap. Text and sticky notes move on a single drag and open for editing on double-click. Switch the pointer to the <strong>Hand</strong> tool to pan the board from anywhere instead of dragging objects.</li>
    <li><strong>Relationship arrows are drawn automatically</strong>: when a query reads another cell's result (<code>FROM &lt;other cell title&gt;</code>) or a chart or table binds to its source query, Arris draws an arrow between the two objects. The arrow sticks to both objects' borders and re-routes automatically as you move or resize them. Right-click an arrow to delete it.</li>
    <li><strong>Resize</strong> a selected object by dragging any of its borders or corner handles.</li>
    <li><strong>Copy, reorder, lock, and delete</strong> from an object's right-click menu: Copy (<kbd>⌘C</kbd>) puts it on the clipboard and Paste (<kbd>⌘V</kbd>) drops a fresh copy nearby, the four restacking actions (Bring to front (<kbd>]</kbd>), Bring forward, Send backward, Send to back (<kbd>[</kbd>)) change its overlap order, Lock freezes it (a locked object can't be moved or resized until you unlock it), and Delete removes it.</li>
    <li><strong>Pan</strong> by dragging the empty canvas, and <strong>zoom</strong> with the scroll wheel or the controls in the corner.</li>
    <li><strong>Delete</strong> a selected object with <kbd>Delete</kbd> or <kbd>Backspace</kbd>.</li>
    <li><strong>Run</strong> a query object at any time with its Run button to refresh the tables and charts bound to it, or hit <strong>Run all</strong> at the right end of the toolbar to run every query on the board at once (each query's upstream cells run first).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="saving">Saving</h2>

  <p>
    A board is saved with your workspace, so it survives closing and reopening the tab and restarting
    Arris. Closed boards are listed in the <strong>Canvas</strong> section of the left sidebar
    alongside SQL consoles and notebooks; click one to reopen it. Reopening a board fits the view to
    its objects, so you always land on your work rather than an empty patch of the infinite board.
    Query results are not saved with the board; reopen a canvas and run its query objects to refresh
    the data.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
